 [[HDR10]]. It requires 25% more bandwidth than standard 8{{nbsp}}bpc video.\n\nHDR extensions were defined in version 1.4 of the DisplayPort standard. Some displays support these HDR extensions, but may only implement HBR2 transmission mode if the extra bandwidth of HBR3 is unnecessary (for example, on 4K 60{{nbsp}}Hz HDR displays). Since there is no definition of what constitutes a \"DisplayPort 1.4\" device, some manufacturers may choose to label these as \"DP 1.2\" devices despite their support for DP 1.4 HDR extensions.<ref>{{cite web |title=LG 27UK650-W 4K UHD LED Monitor |url=https://www.lg.com/us/monitors/lg-27UK650-W-4k-uhd-led-monitor |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118183112/https://www.lg.com/us/monitors/lg-27UK650-W-4k-uhd-led-monitor |archive-date=18 November 2018}}</ref> As a result, DisplayPort \"version numbers\" should not be used as an indicator of HDR support.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|-\n! colspan=11 style=\"height:2.5em;\" | Limits for uncompressed RGB / {{YCbCr}} 4:4:4 video only\n|-\n! colspan=4 | Video Format\n! colspan=7 | Transmission Mode / Maximum Data Rate{{efn|Only a portion of DisplayPort's bandwidth is used for carrying video data. DisplayPort versions 1.0{{ndash}}1.4a use 8b/10b encoding, which means that 80% of the bits transmitted across the link represent data, and the other 20% are used for encoding purposes. The maximum bandwidth of RBR, HBR, HBR2, and HBR3 (6.48, 10.8, 21.6, and 32.4{{nbsp}}Gbit/s) therefore transport video data at rates of 5.184, 8.64, 17.28, and 25.92{{nbsp}}Gbit/s. DisplayPort version 2.0 uses 128b/132b encoding, and therefore the maximum bandwidths of UHBR 10, 13.5, and 20 (40, 54, and 80{{nbsp}}Gbit/s) transport data at rates of 39.69, 52.22, and 77.37{{nbsp}}Gbit/s.}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Shorthand\n! rowspan=2 | Resolution\n! rowspan=2 | Refresh<br />Rate (Hz)\n! rowspan=2 | Data Rate<br />Required{{efn|These data rates are for uncompressed 10{{nbsp}}bpc (30{{nbsp}}bit/px) color depth with RGB or YC<sub>B</sub>C<sub>R</sub> 4:4:4 color format and CVT-R2 timing. Uncompressed data rate for RGB video in bits per second is calculated as bits per pixel &times; pixels per frame &times; frames per second. Pixels per frame includes blanking intervals as defined by [[Coordinated Video Timings|CVT-R2]].}}\n! RBR\n! HBR\n! HBR2\n! HBR3\n! UHBR 10\n! UHBR 13.5\n! UHBR 20\n|-\n!5.184{{nbsp}}Gbit/s\n!8.64{{nbsp}}Gbit/s\n!17.28{{nbsp}}Gbit/s\n!25.92{{nbsp}}Gbit/s\n!38.69{{nbsp}}Gbit/s\n!52.22{{nbsp}}Gbit/s\n!77.37{{nbsp}}Gbit/s\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1080p || rowspan=\"5\" | 1920{{resx}}1080 || align=\"right\"|60||align=\"right\"|4.00{{nbsp}}Gbit/s|| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n|                                                     align=\"right\"|100||align=\"right\"|6.80{{nbsp}}Gbit/s|| {{no}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n|                                                     align=\"right\"|120||align=\"right\"|8.24{{nbsp}}Gbit/s|| {{no}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n|                                                     align=\"right\"|144||align=\"right\"|10.00{{nbsp}}Gbit/s|| {{no}} || {{no}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n|                                                     align=\"right\"|240||align=\"right\"|17.50{{nbsp}}Gbit/s|| {{no}} || {{no}} || {{yes2|Yes{{efn|name=close_enough|Although this format slightly exceeds the maximum data rate of this transmission mode with CVT-R2 timing, it is close enough to be achieved with non-standard timings}}}} || {{yes}}  || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | 1440p || rowspan=\"7\" | 2560{{resx}}1440 || align=\"right\"|30||align=\"right\"|3.47{{nbsp}}Gbit/s|| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n|                                                     align=\"right\"|60||ali