}} || {{yes|DPCP{{nbsp}}1.0}} || {{yes|DPCP{{nbsp}}1.0}} || {{yes|DPCP{{nbsp}}1.0}} || {{yes|DPCP{{nbsp}}1.0}} || {{yes|DPCP{{nbsp}}1.0}}\n|-\n| High-bandwidth digital<br />content protection ([[HDCP]]) || {{no}} || {{yes|HDCP{{nbsp}}1.3}}<ref name=\"DP 1.1a\" />{{rp|at=\u00a71.2.6}} || {{yes|HDCP{{nbsp}}1.3}}<ref name=\"DP 1.2\" />{{rp|at=\u00a71.2.6}} || {{yes|HDCP{{nbsp}}2.2}}<ref name=\"DP 1.3 press\" /> || {{yes|HDCP{{nbsp}}2.2}} || {{yes|HDCP{{nbsp}}2.2}}\n|-\n| Dual-mode (DP++) || {{no}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n| Maximum DP++ bandwidth<br />(TMDS Clock) || {{n/a}} || align=center | 4.95{{nbsp}}Gbit/s<br />(165{{nbsp}}MHz) || align=center | 9.00{{nbsp}}Gbit/s<br />(300{{nbsp}}MHz) || align=center | 18.00{{nbsp}}Gbit/s<br />(600{{nbsp}}MHz) || align=center | 18.00{{nbsp}}Gbit/s<br />(600{{nbsp}}MHz)  || align=center | 18.00{{nbsp}}Gbit/s<br />(600{{nbsp}}MHz)\n|-\n| Stereoscopic 3D video || {{no}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n| Multi-stream transport (MST) || {{no}} || {{no}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n| High-dynamic-range video (HDR) || {{no}} || {{no}} || {{no}} || {{no}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n| Display stream compression (DSC) || {{no}} || {{no}} || {{no}} || {{no}} || {{yes|DSC{{nbsp}}1.2}} || {{yes|DSC{{nbsp}}1.2a}}\n|-\n| Panel replay || {{no}} || {{no}} || {{no}} || {{no}} || {{no}} || {{yes}}<ref name=\"DP 2.0 Anandtech\" />\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n===<span id=\"Dual-mode\"></span><span id=\"DisplayPort++\"></span>DisplayPort dual-mode (DP++) ===\n[[File:DisplayPort plus plus.svg|200px|left|thumb|Dual-mode DisplayPort logo]]\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: right\"\n|+ Dual-mode pin mapping\n! DisplayPort pins || DVI/HDMI mode\n|-\n| Main link lane 0 || TMDS channel 2\n|-\n| Main link lane 1 || TMDS channel 1\n|-\n| Main link lane 2 || TMDS channel 0\n|-\n| Main link lane 3 || TMDS clock\n|-\n| AUX CH+ || DDC clock\n|-\n| AUX CH\u2212 || DDC data\n|-\n| DP_PWR || DP_PWR\n|-\n| Hot-plug detect || Hot-plug detect\n|-\n| Config 1 || Cable adapter detect\n|-\n| Config 2 || [[Consumer Electronics Control|CEC]] ''(HDMI only)''\n|}\n\nDisplayPort Dual-Mode (DP++), also called Dual-Mode DisplayPort, is a standard which allows DisplayPort sources to use simple passive adapters to connect to HDMI or DVI displays. Dual-mode is an optional feature, so not all DisplayPort sources necessarily support DVI/HDMI passive adapters, though in practice nearly all devices do. Officially, the \"DP++\" logo should be used to indicate a DP port that supports dual-mode, but most modern devices do not use the logo.\n\nDevices which implement dual-mode will detect that a DVI or HDMI adapter is attached, and send DVI/HDMI TMDS signals instead of DisplayPort signals. The original DisplayPort Dual-Mode standard (version 1.0), used in DisplayPort{{nbsp}}1.1 devices, only supported TMDS clock speeds of up to 165{{nbsp}}MHz (4.95{{nbsp}}Gbit/s bandwidth). This is equivalent to HDMI{{nbsp}}1.2, and is sufficient for up to 1920{{resx}}1200 at 60{{nbsp}}Hz.\n\nIn 2013, VESA released the Dual-Mode 1.1 standard, which added support for up to a 300{{nbsp}}MHz TMDS clock (9.00{{nbsp}}Gbit/s bandwidth), and is used in newer DisplayPort{{nbsp}}1.2 devices. This is slightly less than the 340{{nbsp}}MHz maximum of HDMI{{nbsp}}1.4, and is sufficient for up to 1920{{resx}}1080 at 120{{nbsp}}Hz, 2560{{resx}}1440 at 60{{nbsp}}Hz, or 3840{{resx}}2160 at 30{{nbsp}}Hz. Older adapters, which were only capable of the 165{{nbsp}}MHz speed, were retroactively termed \"Type{{nbsp}}1\" adapters, with the new 300{{nbsp}}MHz adapters being called \"Type{{nbsp}}2\".<ref>{{cite web |title=VESA Introduces Updated Dual-Mode Standard for Higher Resolution Interoperability with HDMI Displays |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510051652/https://www.vesa.org/news/vesa-introduces-updated-dual-mode-standard-for-higher-resolution-interoperability-with-hdmi-displays/ |archive-date=10 May 2018 |url=http://www.vesa.org/featured-articles/vesa-introduces-updated-dual-mode-standard-for-higher-resolution-interoperability-with-hdmi-displays/ |publisher=VESA |date=31 January 2013 |accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nWith the release of the DisplayPort{{nbsp}}1.3 standard, VESA added dual-mode support for up to a 600{{nbsp}}MHz TMDS clock (18.00{{nbsp}}Gbit/s bandwidth), the full bandwidth of HDMI{{nbsp}}2.0. This is sufficient for 1920{{resx}}1080 at 240{{nbsp}}Hz, 2560{{resx}}1440 at 144{{nbsp}}Hz, or 3840{{resx}}2160 at 60{{nbsp}}Hz. However, no passive adapters capable of the 600{{nbsp}}MHz dual-mode speed have been produced as of 2018.\n\n==== Dual-mode limitations ====\n\n[[File:DP to DVI converter unmounted.jpg|thumb|Picture of a DisplayPort to DVI adapter after removing its enclosure. The chip on the board converts the voltage levels generated by the dual-mode DisplayPort device to be compatible with a DVI monitor.]]\n\n* Limited adapter speed{{Snd}} Although the pinout and digital signal values transmitted by the DP port are identical to a native DVI/HDMI source, the signals are transmitted at DisplayPort's native voltage (3.3{{nbsp}}V) instead of the 5{{nbsp}}V used by DVI and HDMI. As a result, dual-mode adapters must contain a level-shifter circuit which changes the voltage. The presence of this circuit places a limit on how quickly the adapter can operate, and therefore newer adapters are required for each higher speed added to the standard.\n* Unidirectional{{Snd}} Although the dual-mode standard specifies a method for DisplayPort ''sources'' to output DVI/HDMI signals using simple passive adapters, there is no counterpart standard to give DisplayPort displays the ability to ''receive'' DVI/HDMI input signals through passive adapters. As a result, DisplayPort displays can only receive native DisplayPort signals; any DVI or HDMI input signals must be converted to the DisplayPort format with an active conversion device. DVI and HDMI sources cannot be connected to DisplayPort displays using passive adapters.\n* Single-link DVI only{{Snd}} Since DisplayPort dual-mode operates by using the pins of the DisplayPort connector to send DVI/HDMI signals, the 20-pin DisplayPort connector can only produce a ''single-link'' DVI signal (which uses 19 pins). A ''dual-link DVI'' signal uses 25 pins, and is therefore impossible to transmit natively from a DisplayPort connector through a passive adapter. Dual-link DVI signals can only be produced by converting from native DisplayPort output signals with an active conversion device.\n* Unavailable on USB-C{{Snd}} The ''DisplayPort Alternate Mode'' specification for sending DisplayPort signals over a [[USB-C]] cable does not include support for the dual-mode protocol. As a result, DP-to-DVI and DP-to-HDMI passive adapters do not function when chained from a USB-C to DP adapter.\n\n=== Multi-Stream Transport (MST) {{Anchor|Multi-Stream Transport|MST|Multiple displays on single DisplayPort connector}} ===\n\n'''Multi-Stream Transport''' is a feature first introduced in the DisplayPort{{nbsp}}1.2 standard. It allows multiple independent displays to be driven from a single DP port on the source devices by [[multiplexing]] several video streams into a single stream and sending it to a ''branch device'', which demultiplexes the signal into the original streams. Branch devices are commonly found in the form of an MST hub, which plugs into a single DP input port and provides multiple outputs, but it can also be implemented on a display internally to provide a DP output port for daisy-chaining, effectively embedding a 2-port MST hub inside the display.<ref name=\"DP 1.2\" />{{rp|at=Fig. 2-59}}<ref>{{cite web|title=DisplayPortTM Ver.1.2 Overview |url=http://www.vesa.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/DisplayPort-DevCon-Presentation-DP-1.2-Dec-2010-rev-2b.pdf|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> Theoretically, up to 63 displays can be supported,<ref name=\"DP 1.2\" />{{rp|page=20}} but the combined data rate requirements of all the displays cannot exceed the limits of a single DP port (17.28{{nbsp}}Gbit/s for a DP{{nbsp}}1.2 port, or 25.92{{nbsp}}Gbit/s for a DP 1.3/1.4 port). In addition, the maximum number of links between the source and any device (i.e. the maximum length of a daisy-chain) is 7,<ref name=\"DP 1.2\" />{{rp|at=\u00a72.5.2}} and the maximum number of physical output ports on each branch device (such as a hub) is 7.<ref name=\"DP 1.2\" />{{rp|at=\u00a72.5.1}} With the release of MST, standard single-display operation has been retroactively named \"SST\" mode (Single-Stream Transport).\n\nDaisy-chaining is a feature that must be specifically supported by each intermediary display; not all DisplayPort{{nbsp}}1.2 devices support it. Daisy-chaining requires a dedicated DisplayPort ''output'' port on the display. Standard DisplayPort ''input'' ports found on most displays cannot be used as a daisy-chain output. Only the last display in the daisy-chain does not need to support the feature specifically or have a DP output port. DisplayPort{{nbsp}}1.1 displays can also be connected to MST hubs, and can be part of a DisplayPort daisy-chain if it is the last display in the chain.<ref name=\"DP 1.2\" />{{rp|at=\u00a72.5.1}}\n\nThe host system's software also needs to support MST for hubs or daisy-chains to work. While [[Microsoft]] [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] environments have full support for it, [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] operating systems currently do not support MST hubs or DisplayPort daisy-chaining as of macOS 10.13 (\"High Sierra\").<ref>{{cite web |title=Display Daisy-Chaining with High Sierra |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180513010057/https://apple.stackexchange.com/questions/300020/display-daisy-chaining-with-high-sierra |archive-date=13 May 2018 |url=https://apple.stackexchange.com/questions/300020/display-daisy-chaining-with-high-sierra |date=27 September 2017 |accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=MBPr 2015, 2.5GHz i7 \u2013 Daisychaining 2 Dell U2414H 61 Screens |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207155822/https://apple.stackexchange.com/questions/189542/mbpr-2015-2-5ghz-i7-daisychaining-2-dell-u2414h-61-screens |archive-date=7 December 2016 |url=https://apple.stackexchange.com/questions/189542/mbpr-2015-2-5ghz-i7-daisychaining-2-dell-u2414h-61-screens |date=31 May 2015 |accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nDisplayPort-to-DVI and DisplayPort-to-HDMI adapters/cables may or may not function from an MST output port; support for this depends on the specific device.{{Citation needed|reason=Needs a non-OR source (see talk page)|date=July 2018}}\n\nMST is supported by USB Type-C DisplayPort Alternate Mode, so standard DisplayPort daisy-chains and MST hubs do function from Type-C sources with a simple Type-C to DisplayPort adapter.<ref>{{cite web | title=Google's USB Type-C to DP Adapter \"DingDong\" | url= https://www.chromium.org/chromium-os/dingdong | accessdate = August 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== High dynamic range (HDR) ===\n\n{{main|High-dynamic-range video}}\n\nSupport for HDR video was introduced in DisplayPort{{nbsp}}1.4. It implements the CTA 861.3 standard for transport of static HDR metadata in EDID.<ref name=\"DP 1.4 press\" />\n\n=== Content protection {{anchor|Digital Rights Management (DRM)}} ===\n\nDisplayPort{{nbsp}}1.0 includes optional ''DPCP'' (DisplayPort Content Protection) from [[Philips]], which uses 128-bit [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES]] encryption. It also features full authentication and session key establishment. Each encryption session is independent, and it has an independent revocation system. This portion of the standard is licensed separately. It also adds the ability to verify the proximity of the receiver and transmitter, a technique intended to ensure users are not bypassing the content protection system to send data out to distant, unauthorized users.<ref name=\"DP 1.1a\" />{{rp|at=\u00a76}}\n\nDisplayPort{{nbsp}}1.1 added optional implementation of industry-standard 56-bit HDCP ([[High-bandwidth Digital Content Protection]]) revision 1.3, which requires separate licensing from the Digital Content Protection LLC.<ref name=\"DP 1.1a\" />{{rp|at=\u00a71.2.6}}\n\nDisplayPort{{nbsp}}1.3 added support for HDCP{{nbsp}}2.2, which is also used by HDMI{{nbsp}}2.0.<ref name=\"DP 1.3 press\" />\n\n== Cost ==\n\nVESA, the creators of the DisplayPort standard, state that the standard is royalty-free to implement. However, in March 2015, [[MPEG LA]] issued a press release stating that a royalty rate of $0.20 per unit applies to DisplayPort products manufactured or sold in countries that are covered by one or more of the patents in the MPEG LA license pool, which includes patents from [[Hitachi Maxell]], [[Philips]], [[Lattice Semiconductor]], [[Rambus]], and [[Sony]].<ref name=DisplayPortMPEGLicenseMarch2015>{{cite news |title=MPEG LA Introduces License for DisplayPort |publisher=Business Wire |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20150305006071/en/MPEG-LA-Introduces-License-DisplayPort |date=5 March 2015 |accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=MPEGLAPatents>{{cite web | title=DisplayPort Attachment 1|url=http://www.mpegla.com/main/programs/DisplayPort/Documents/displayport-att1.pdf |date=23 November 2015 | accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref> In response, VESA updated their DisplayPort FAQ page with the following statement:<ref name=DisplayPortFAQ>{{cite news |title=DisplayPort FAQ|url=http://www.displayport.org/faq/ |publisher=Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA)|accessdate=23 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151113134810/http://www.displayport.org/faq/ |archive-date=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n{{quote\n|''MPEG LA is making claims that DisplayPort implementation requires a license and a royalty payment. It is important to note that these are only CLAIMS. Whether these CLAIMS are relevant will likely be decided in a US court.''\n}}\n\nAs of August 2019 VESA's official FAQ no longer contains a statement disputing the MPEG LA royalty fees. [https://www.vesa.org/faqs/#General%20DisplayPort%20FAQs FAQ].\n\nWhile VESA does not charge any per-device royalty fees, VESA requires membership for access to said standards.<ref>{{cite news | title=VESA standards purchasing page | url=https://www.vesa.org/vesa-standards/}}</ref> The minimum cost is presently $5,000 (or $10,000 depending on Annual Corporate Sales Revenue) annually.<ref>{{cite news | title=VESA membership application | url=https://fs16.formsite.com/VESA/form70/index.html }}</ref>\n\n== {{Anchor|Advantages over legacy standards}}Advantages over DVI, VGA and FPD-Link ==\n{{Cleanup list|date=November 2010}}\nIn December 2010, several computer vendors and display makers including Intel, AMD, Dell, Lenovo, Samsung and LG announced they would begin phasing out FPD-Link, VGA, and DVI-I over the next few years, replacing them with DisplayPort and [[HDMI]].<ref name=\"technewsworld1\">{{Cite journal | url = http://www.technewsworld.com/story/VGA-Given-5-Years-to-Live-71420.html | publisher = Tech news world | title = VGA Given 5 Years to Live | date = 9 December 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | url = https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2374034,00.asp?kc=PCRSS03069TX1K0001121 | title = Top PC, Chip, Display Makers to Ditch VGA, DVI | journal = PCMag }}</ref> One notable exception to the list of manufacturers is Nvidia, who has yet{{when|date=March 2019}} to announce any plans regarding future implementation of legacy interfaces.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nDisplayPort has several advantages over VGA, DVI, and FPD-Link.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.st.com/st-web-ui/static/active/en/resource/technical/document/technical_article/CD00271554.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719060349/http://www.st.com/st-web-ui/static/active/en/resource/technical/document/technical_article/CD00271554.pdf |archivedate=19 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* Open standard available to all VESA members{{dubious|Open standard|date=March 2017}} with an extensible standard to help broad adoption<ref>{{Cite journal | url = http://www.vesa.org/vesa-standards/ | publisher = Vesa | title = Standards | accessdate =2016-01-27}}</ref>\n* Fewer lanes with embedded self-clock, reduced [[Electromagnetic interference|EMI]] with data scrambling and [[spread spectrum]] mode\n* Based on a micro-packet protocol\n** Allows easy expansion of the standard with multiple data types\n** Flexible allocation of available bandwidth between audio and video\n** Multiple video streams over single physical connection (version 1.2)\n** Long-distance transmission over alternative physical media such as optical fiber (version 1.1a)\n* High-resolution displays and multiple displays with a single connection, via a hub or daisy-chaining<ref>{{cite web|author=Niels Broekhuijsen |url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/evga-displayport-hub,25464.html |title=EVGA's DisplayPort Hub Available Now |publisher=Tomshardware.com |date= |accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref>\n** HBR2 mode with 17.28{{nbsp}}Gbit/s of effective video bandwidth allows four simultaneous 1080p60 displays (CEA-861 timings), two 2560 \u00d7 1600 \u00d7 30 bit @ 120{{nbsp}}Hz (CVT-R timings), or [[4K UHDTV|4K UHD]] @ 60{{nbsp}}Hz<ref group=\"note\">Dual-link DVI is limited in resolution and speed by the quality and therefore the bandwidth of the DVI cable, the quality of the transmitter, and the quality of the receiver; can only drive one monitor at a time; and cannot send audio data. HDMI 1.3 and 1.4 are limited to effectively 8.16{{nbsp}}Gbit/s or 340{{nbsp}}MHz (though actual devices are limited to 225\u2013300{{nbsp}}MHz{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}), and can only drive one monitor at a time. [[VGA connector]]s have no defined maximum resolution or speed, but their analog nature limits their bandwidth, though can provide long cabling only limited by appropriate shielding.</ref>\n** HBR3 mode with 25.92{{nbsp}}Gbit/s of effective video bandwidth, using CVT-R2 timings, allows eight simultaneous 1080p displays (1920 \u00d7 1080) @ 60{{nbsp}}Hz, [[stereoscopic]] [[4K UHDTV|4K UHD]] (3840 \u00d7 2160) @ 120{{nbsp}}Hz, or 5120 \u00d7 2880 @ 60{{nbsp}}Hz each using 24 bit RGB, and up to [[8K UHDTV|8K UHD]] (7680 \u00d7 4320) @ 60{{nbsp}}Hz using 4:2:0 subsampling<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/VESA-veroeffentlicht-DisplayPort-1-3-2392134.html|title=VESA ver\u00f6ffentlicht DisplayPort 1.3|author=Moritz F\u00f6rster|date=16 September 2014|work=heise online|accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref>\n* Designed to work for internal chip-to-chip communication\n** Aimed at replacing internal FPD-Link links to display panels with a unified link interface\n** Compatible with low-voltage signaling used with [[90 nanometer|sub-micron]] [[CMOS]] fabrication\n** Can drive display panels directly, eliminating scaling and control circuits and allowing for cheaper and slimmer displays\n* Link training with adjustable amplitude and preemphasis adapts to differing cable lengths and signal quality\n** Reduced bandwidth transmission for {{convert|15|m|ft|adj=mid}} cable, at least 1920 \u00d7 1080p @ 60{{nbsp}}Hz at 24 bits per pixel\n** Full bandwidth transmission for {{convert|3|m|ft}}\n* High-speed auxiliary channel for DDC, EDID, MCCS, DPMS, HDCP, adapter identification etc. traffic\n** Can be used for transmitting bi-directional USB, touch-panel data, [[Consumer Electronics Control|CEC]], etc.\n* Self-latching connector\n\n== Comparison with HDMI ==\nAlthough DisplayPort has much of the same functionality as [[HDMI]], it is a complementary connection used in different scenarios.<ref name=\"dpfaq\">{{Cite news |title=FAQ Archive{{Snd}} DisplayPort |publisher=VESA |url=http://www.displayport.org/faq/faq-archive/ |accessdate=22 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Direct2Dell_DPvsHDMI\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.dell.com/en-us/46464/|title=The Truth About DisplayPort vs. HDMI|author=|date=|work=dell.com|accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref> A [[#DisplayPort dual-mode (DP++)|dual-mode DisplayPort port]] can emit an HDMI signal via a passive adapter.\n\n* In 2008, [[HDMI Licensing, LLC]] charged an annual fee of US$10,000 to each high-volume manufacturer and a per-unit royalty rate of US$0.04 to US$0.15.<ref>{{Cite news |title=HDMI Adopter Terms |website=hdmi.org |publisher=HDMI Licensing |url=http://www.hdmi.org/manufacturer/terms.aspx |accessdate=23 June 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218170701/http://www.hdmi.org/manufacturer/terms.aspx |archive-date=18 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{Needs update|date=June 2019}} HDMI Licensing, LLC countered the \"royalty-free\" claim by pointing out that the DisplayPort specification states that companies can charge a royalty rate for DisplayPort implementation.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Interview with Steve Venuti from HDMI Licensing |publisher=HDMI Licensing | url= http://www.hdmi.org/pdf/2009_10_Veritas_Visus_Venuti_Interview.pdf |website=hdmi.org | accessdate= 2016-01-27}}</ref> \n* DisplayPort 1.2 has more bandwidth at 21.6{{nbsp}}Gbit/s<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.anandtech.com/show/4563/zotac-releases-displayport-to-dual-hdmi-adapter | title= Zotac releases DisplayPort to dual HDMI adapter | date = 2 August 2011 | publisher = Anandtech |accessdate=23 January 2012}}</ref> (17.28{{nbsp}}Gbit/s with overhead removed) as opposed to HDMI 2.0's 18{{nbsp}}Gbit/s<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.hdmi.org/manufacturer/hdmi_2_0/hdmi_2_0_faq.aspx |title=FAQ for HDMI 2.0 |publisher=HDMI |accessdate=29 November 2013}}</ref> (14.4{{nbsp}}Gbit/s with overhead removed). \n* DisplayPort 1.3 raises that to 32.4{{nbsp}}Gbit/s (25.92{{nbsp}}Gbit/s with overhead removed), and HDMI 2.1 raises that up to 48{{nbsp}}Gbit/s (42.67{{nbsp;}}Gbit/s with overhead removed), adding  an additional TMDS link in place of clock lane. DisplayPort also has the ability to share this bandwidth with [[DisplayPort#Multiple displays on single DisplayPort connector|multiple streams]] of audio and video to separate devices.\n* DisplayPort in native mode lacks some HDMI features such as [[Consumer Electronics Control]] (CEC) commands. The CEC bus allows linking multiple sources with a single display and controlling any of these devices from any remote.<ref name=\"DP 1.1a\" /><ref name=\"HDMI1.3a\">{{cite news|url=http://www.microprocessor.org/HDMISpecification13a.pdf|title=HDMI Specification 1.3a|date=10 November 2006|publisher=HDMI Licensing, LLC|accessdate=1 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305072940/http://www.microprocessor.org/HDMISpecification13a.pdf|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>http://www.quantumdata.com/pdf/CEC_White_Paper.pdf</ref> DisplayPort 1.3 added the possibility of transmitting [[Consumer Electronics Control|CEC]] commands over the AUX channel<ref>{{cite web|title=Linux drm: add support for DisplayPort CEC-Tunneling-over-AUX | url=https://patchwork.kernel.org/patch/10066347/ | author = Hans Verkuil | publisher = Cisco |\ndate = 20 November 2017 | accessdate = 3 January 2018 }}</ref> From its very first version HDMI features CEC to support connecting ''multiple sources to a single display'' as is typical for a TV screen. The other way round, [[DisplayPort#Multiple displays on single DisplayPort connector|Multi-Stream Transport]] allows connecting ''multiple displays to a single computer source''. This reflects the facts that [[HDMI]] originated from ''consumer electronics'' companies whereas DisplayPort is owned by [[VESA]] which started as an organization for ''computer'' standards. \n* HDMI can accept much longer max cable length than DisplayPort (30 meters vs 3 meters).<ref>https://www.planar.com/blog/2014/12/15/displayport-13-vs-hdmi-20/</ref>\n* HDMI uses unique Vendor-Specific Block structure, which allows for features such as additional color spaces. However, these features can be defined by [[Extended Display Identification Data#CEA EDID Timing Extension Version 3 data format|CEA EDID extensions]].{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n* Both HDMI and DisplayPort have published specification for transmitting their signal over the [[USB-C]] connector. For more details, see {{Section link|USB-C|Alternate Mode partner specifications}} and List of devices with video output over USB-C.\n\n== Market share ==\nFigures from [[International Data Corporation|IDC]] show that 5.1% of commercial desktops and 2.1% of commercial notebooks released in 2009 featured DisplayPort.<ref name=\"technewsworld1\"/> The main factor behind this was the phase-out of VGA, and that both Intel and AMD planned to stop building products with FPD-Link by 2013. Nearly 70% of LCD monitors sold in August 2014 in the US, UK, Germany, Japan, and China were equipped with HDMI/DisplayPort technology, up 7.5% on the year, according to Digitimes Research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitimes.com/news/a20140901PD209.html|title=Digitimes Research: Proportion of HDMI/DisplayPort technology in LCD monitors increases 7.5pp in August|website=DIGITIMES}}</ref> IHS Markit, an analytics firm, forecast that DisplayPort would surpass [[HDMI]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://technology.ihs.com/599141/displayport-expected-to-surpass-hdmi-in-2019|title=DisplayPort expected to surpass HDMI in 2019 - IHS Technology|website=technology.ihs.com}}</ref>\n\n== Companion standards ==\n\n=== Mini DisplayPort ===\n{{Main|Mini DisplayPort}}\n''Mini DisplayPort'' (mDP) is a standard announced by Apple in the fourth quarter of 2008. Shortly after announcing Mini DisplayPort, Apple announced that it would license the connector technology with no fee. The following year, in early 2009, VESA announced that Mini DisplayPort would be included in the upcoming DisplayPort 1.2 specification.\nOn 24 February 2011, Apple and Intel announced [[Thunderbolt (interface)|Thunderbolt]], a successor to Mini DisplayPort which adds support for [[PCI Express]] data connections while maintaining backwards compatibility with Mini DisplayPort based peripherals.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://newsroom.intel.com/community/intel_newsroom/blog/2011/02/24/thunderbolt-technology-the-fastest-data-connection-to-your-pc-just-arrived |title=Thunderbolt Technology: The Fastest Data Connection to Your PC Just Arrived |publisher=Intel |date=24 February 2011 |accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Micro DisplayPort ===\n''Micro DisplayPort'' would have targeted systems that need ultra-compact connectors, such as phones, tablets and ultra-portable notebook computers. This standard would have been physically smaller than the currently available Mini DisplayPort connectors. The standard was expected to be released by Q2 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.displayport.org/pr/vesa-begins-development-of-micro-displayport-connector-standard/ |title=VESA Begins Development of micro-DisplayPort Connector Standard |publisher=DisplayPort |date=23 October 2013 |accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref>\nThis project seems aborted to be replaced by '''DisplayPort Alt Mode for [[USB-C|USB Type-C]] Standard.'''<ref>{{cite web|last1=VESA|first1=displayport|title=FAQ|url=https://www.displayport.org/faq/#DisplayPort|website=displayport.org|publisher=VESA|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== DDM ===\n''Direct Drive Monitor'' (DDM) 1.0 standard was approved in December 2008. It allows for controller-less monitors where the display panel is directly driven by the DisplayPort signal, although the available resolutions and color depth are limited to two-lane operation.\n\n=== Display Stream Compression ===\n''Display Stream Compression'' (DSC) is a [[Video Electronics Standards Association|VESA]]-developed low-latency compression algorithm to overcome the limitations posed by sending high-resolution video over physical media of limited bandwidth. It is a visually lossless low-latency algorithm based on [[delta modulation|delta PCM]] coding and [[YCoCg|YCoCg-R]] color space; it allows increased resolutions and color depths and reduced power consumption.<ref name=DSC>{{cite press |url=https://www.vesa.org/news/vesa-finalizes-requirements-for-display-stream-compression-standard/ |title=VESA Finalizes Requirements for Display Stream Compression Standard |publisher=VESA |date=24 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=vesa-etp200>http://www.vesa.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/VESA_DSC-ETP200.pdf</ref>\n\nDSC has been tested to meet the requirements of ISO/IEC 29170-2 ''Evaluation procedure for nearly lossless coding'' using various test patterns, noise, subpixel-rendered text ([[ClearType]]), UI captures, and photo and video images.<ref name=vesa-etp200/>\n\nDSC version 1.0 was released on 10 March 2014, but was soon deprecated by DSC version 1.1 released on 1 August 2014. The DSC standard supports up to 3:1 compression ratio with constant or variable bit rate, 4:4:4 [[chroma subsampling]], optional 4:2:2 conversion and 6/8/10/12 bits per color component.\n\nDSC version 1.2 was released on 27 January 2016 and is included with DisplayPort 1.4; version 1.2a was released on 18 January 2017. The update includes native encoding of 4:2:2 and 4:2:0 formats in pixel containers, 14/16 bits per color, and minor modifications to the encoding algorithm.\n\nDSC compression works on a horizontal line of pixels encoded using groups of three consecutive pixels for native 4:4:4 and simple 4:2:2 formats, or six pixels (three compressed containers) for native 4:2:2 and 4:2:0 formats. If RGB encoding is used, it is first converted to reversible YCgCo. Simple conversion from 4:2:2 to 4:4:4 can add missing chroma samples by interpolating neighboring pixels. Each luma component is coded separately using three independent substreams (four substreams in native 4:2:2 mode). Prediction step is performed using one of the three modes: modified median adaptive coding (MMAP) algorithm similar to the one used by [[JPEG-LS]], block prediction (optional for decoders due to high computational complexity, negotiated at DSC handshake), and midpoint prediction. Bit rate control algorithm tracks color flatness and buffer fullness to adjust the quantization bit depth for a pixel group in a way that minimizes compression artifacts while staying within the bitrate limits. Repeating recent pixels can be stored in 32-entry Indexed Color History (ICH) buffer, which can be referenced directly by each group in a slice; this improves compression quality of computer-generated images. Alternatively, prediction residuals are computed and encoded with [[entropy coding]] algorithm based on delta size unit-variable length coding (DSU-VLC). Encoded pixel groups are then combined into slices of various height and width; common combinations include 100% or 25% picture width, and 8-, 32-, or 108-line height.\n\nOn 4 January 2017, [[HDMI 2.1]] was announced which supports up to [[10K resolution]] and uses DSC 1.2 for video that is higher than 8K resolution with 4:2:0 [[chroma subsampling]].<ref name=HDMI21PressRelease>{{cite news |url=http://www.hdmi.org/press/press_release.aspx?prid=145 |title=HDMI Forum announces version 2.1 of the HDMI specification |publisher=HDMI.org |date=2017-01-04 |accessdate=2017-01-10}}</ref><ref name=HDMI21Introduction>{{cite news |url=http://www.hdmi.org/manufacturer/hdmi_2_1/index.aspx |title=Introducing HDMI 2.1 |publisher=HDMI.org |accessdate=2017-01-10}}</ref><ref name=HDMI21January2017Anandtech>{{cite news |url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/11003/hdmi-21-announced-8kp60-48gbps-cable |title=HDMI 2.1 Announced|author=Anton Shilov |publisher=Anandtech |date=2017-01-05 |accessdate=2017-01-10}}</ref>\n\n=== eDP ===\n''Embedded DisplayPort'' (eDP) is a display panel interface standard for portable and embedded devices. It defines the signaling interface between graphics cards and integrated displays. The various revisions of eDP are based on existing DisplayPort standards. However, version numbers between the two standards are not interchangeable. For instance, eDP version 1.4 is based on DisplayPort 1.2, while eDP version 1.4a is based on DisplayPort 1.3. In practice, embedded DisplayPort has displaced [[FPD-Link|LVDS]] as the predominant panel interface in modern laptops.\n\neDP 1.0 was adopted in December 2008.<ref name=\"eDP11a\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vesa.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/PR22309eDP1_1a1.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707045940/http://www.vesa.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/PR22309eDP1_1a1.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Embedded DisplayPort Standard Ready from VESA |publisher=VESA |date=23 February 2009 }}</ref> It included advanced power-saving features such as seamless refresh rate switching. \nVersion 1.1 was approved in October 2009 followed by version 1.1a in November 2009. \nVersion 1.2 was approved in May 2010 and includes DisplayPort 1.2 HBR2 data rates, 120{{nbsp}}Hz [[sequential color]] monitors, and a new display panel control protocol that works through the AUX channel.<ref name= DevCon2010 /> \nVersion 1.3 was published in February 2011; it includes a new optional Panel Self-Refresh (PSR) feature developed to save system power and further extend battery life in portable PC systems.<ref>{{Cite journal | url = http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110207005402/en/VESA-%C2%AE-Issues-Updated-Embedded-DisplayPort%C2%AE-Standard | title = VESA Issues Updated Embedded DisplayPort Standard | publisher = Business Wire | accessdate =2016-01-27}}</ref> PSR mode allows the GPU to enter a power saving state in between frame updates by including [[framebuffer]] memory in the display panel controller.<ref name = DevCon2010 /> \nVersion 1.4 was released in February 2013; it reduces power consumption through partial-frame updates in PSR mode, regional backlight control, lower interface voltages, and additional link rates; the auxiliary channel supports multi-touch panel data to accommodate different form factors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vesa.org/featured-articles/vesa-improves-mobile-device-battery-life-and-display-performance-with-upcoming-release-of-embedded-displayport-edp-version-1-4/ |title=Mobile Battery Life and Display Performance Improves with Upcoming Release of eDP 1.4 |publisher=VESA |date=10 September 2012 |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref> Version 1.4a was published in February 2015; the underlying DisplayPort version was updated to 1.3 in order to support HBR3 data rates, Display Stream Compression 1.1, Segmented Panel Displays, and partial updates for Panel Self-Refresh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vesa.org/featured-articles/vesa-publishes-embedded-displayport-edp-standard-version-1-4a/|title=VESA Publishes Embedded DisplayPort (eDP) Standard Version 1.4a|author=|date=|work=vesa.org|accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref>  Version 1.4b was published in October 2015; its protocol refinements and clarifications are intended to enable adoption of eDP 1.4b in devices by mid-2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vesa.org/featured-articles/vesa-rolls-out-production-ready-embedded-displayport-standard-1-4-for-mobile-personal-computing-devices/ |title=VESA Rolls Out Production-Ready Embedded DisplayPort Standard 1.4 for Mobile Personal Computing Devices |publisher=VESA |date=27 October 2015 |accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== iDP ===\n''Internal DisplayPort'' (iDP) 1.0 was approved in April 2010. The iDP standard defines an internal link between a digital TV [[system on a chip]] controller and the display panel's timing controller. It aims to replace currently used internal [[FPD-Link]] lanes with DisplayPort connection.<ref name=\"iDP\">{{cite web | url = http://www.displayport.org/cms/sites/default/files/downloads/press-releases/iDP_VESA_PR.pdf | title= VESA Issues Internal DisplayPort Standard for Flat Panel TVs | publisher= VESA |date=10 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726000532/http://www.displayport.org/cms/sites/default/files/downloads/press-releases/iDP_VESA_PR.pdf|archive-date=26 July 2011}}</ref> iDP features unique physical interface and protocols, which are not directly compatible with DisplayPort and are not applicable to external connection, however they enable very high resolution and refresh rates while providing simplicity and extensibility.<ref name = DevCon2010 /> iDP features non-variable 2.7{{nbsp}}GHz clock and is nominally rated at 3.24{{nbsp}}Gbit/s data rate per lane, with up to sixteen lanes in a ''bank'', resulting in six-fold decrease in wiring requirements over FPD-Link for a 1080p24 signal; other data rates are also possible. iDP was built with simplicity in mind and it doesn't have AUX channel, content protection, or multiple streams; however it does have frame sequential and line interleaved stereo 3D.<ref name=DevCon2010 />\n\n=== PDMI ===\n''Portable Digital Media Interface'' ([[PDMI]]) is an interconnection between docking stations/display devices and portable media players, which includes 2-lane DisplayPort v1.1a connection. It has been ratified in February 2010 as [[ANSI]]/[[Consumer Electronics Association|CEA]]-2017-A.\n\n=== wDP ===\n''Wireless DisplayPort'' (''wDP'') enables DisplayPort 1.2 bandwidth and feature set for cable-free applications operating in 60{{nbsp}}GHz radio band; it was announced on November 2010 by [[Wireless Gigabit Alliance|WiGig Alliance]] and VESA as a cooperative effort.<ref>{{Cite journal | url = http://wirelessgigabitalliance.org/news/wigig%E2%84%A2-alliance-and-vesa%C2%AE-to-collaborate-on-next-generation-wireless-displayport/ | publisher = Wireless Gigabit Alliance | title = WiGig Alliance and VESA to Collaborate on Next Generation Wireless DisplayPort }}</ref>\n\n=== SlimPort ===\n[[File:A SlimPort-to-HDMI adapter, made by Analogix.jpg|thumb|right|A SlimPort-to-HDMI adapter, made by Analogix]]\n\n''SlimPort'', a brand of Analogix products,<ref>{{cite web |title=VESA Experiences Acceleration of MyDP Standard Adoption in Mobile Devices |url=http://www.vesa.org/news/vesa-experiences-acceleration-of-mydp-standard-adoption-in-mobile-devices/ |access-date=10 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322100508/http://www.vesa.org/news/vesa-experiences-acceleration-of-mydp-standard-adoption-in-mobile-devices/ |archive-date=22 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> complies with ''Mobility DisplayPort'', also known as ''MyDP'', which is an industry standard for a mobile audio/video Interface, providing connectivity from mobile devices to external displays and HDTVs. SlimPort implements the transmission of video up to 4K-UltraHD and up to eight channels of audio over the [[micro-USB]] connector to an external converter accessory or display device. SlimPort products support seamless connectivity to DisplayPort, HDMI and VGA displays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.slimportconnect.com/support/ |title=Support{{Snd}} Slimport |publisher=Us.slimportconnect.com |date=18 July 2013 |accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> The MyDP standard was released in June 2012,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vesa.org/news/vesa-enables-mobile-devices-to-share-full-hd-video-and-3d-content-on-any-display-with-release-of-mydp-standard/ |title=Releases MyDP Standard |publisher=VESA |date=27 June 2012 |accessdate=10 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317100300/http://www.vesa.org/news/vesa-enables-mobile-devices-to-share-full-hd-video-and-3d-content-on-any-display-with-release-of-mydp-standard/ |archive-date=17 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and the first product to use SlimPort was [[Google]]'s [[Nexus 4]] smartphone.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vesa.org/featured-articles/vesa-experiences-acceleration-of-mydp-standard-adoption-in-mobile-devices/ |title=Experiences Acceleration of MyDP Standard Adoption in Mobile Devices |publisher=VESA |date=9 November 2012 |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref> Some LG smartphones in [[LG G series]] also adopted SlimPort.\n\nSlimPort is an alternative to [[Mobile High-Definition Link]] (MHL).<ref>{{cite web |title=Hands on with the Analogix SlimPort microUSB to HDMI and VGA adapters |url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/6499/hands-on-with-the-analogix-slimport-microusb-to-hdmi-and-vga-adapters |work=AnandTech |accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=SlimPort |url=http://www.slimportconnect.com/ |accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== DisplayID ===\n{{Main|DisplayID}}\n''DisplayID'' is designed to replace the [[Extended display identification data|E-EDID]] standard. DisplayID features variable-length structures which encompass all existing [[EDID]] extensions as well as new extensions for [[3D displays]] and embedded displays.\n\nThe latest version 1.3 (announced on 23 September 2013) adds enhanced support for tiled display topologies; it allows better identification of multiple video streams, and reports bezel size and locations.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vesa.org/news/vesa-refreshes-displayid-standard-to-support-higher-resolutions-and-tiled-displays/ | title = VESA Refreshes DisplayID Standard to Support Higher Resolutions and Tiled Displays | date = 23 September 2013 | accessdate = 24 December 2013 | publisher = vesa.org | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150208120440/http://www.vesa.org/news/vesa-refreshes-displayid-standard-to-support-higher-resolutions-and-tiled-displays/ | archive-date = 8 February 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref>  As of December 2013, many current 4K displays use a tiled topology, but lack a standard way to report to the video source which tile is left and which is right. These early 4K displays, for manufacturing reasons, typically use two 1920\u00d72160 panels laminated together and are currently generally treated as multiple-monitor setups.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.tomshardware.com/reviews/pq321q-4k-gaming,3620.html | title = Gaming At 3840x2160: Is Your PC Ready For A 4K Display? | date = 19 September 2013 | accessdate = 26 December 2013 | publisher = www.tomshardware.com}}</ref> DisplayID 1.3 also allows 8K display discovery, and has applications in stereo 3D, where multiple video streams are used.\n\n=== DockPort ===\n{{Main|DockPort}}\n''DockPort'', formerly known as ''Lightning Bolt'', is an extension to DisplayPort to include [[USB 3.0]] data as well as power for charging portable devices from attached external displays. Originally developed by AMD and Texas Instruments, it has been announced as a VESA specification in 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/7649/dockport-adopted-as-official-extension-to-displayport-standard | title=MD/TI's DockPort Adopted As Official Extension to DisplayPort Standard | accessdate = 12 January 2014 | publisher = anandtech.com}}</ref>\n\n=== USB-C ===\n{{main|USB-C}}\nOn 22 September 2014, VESA published the ''DisplayPort Alternate Mode on USB Type-C Connector Standard'', a specification on how to send DisplayPort signals over the newly released [[USB-C]] connector. One, two or all four of the differential pairs that USB uses for the SuperSpeed bus can be configured dynamically to be used for DisplayPort lanes. In the first two cases, the connector still can carry a full SuperSpeed signal; in the latter case, at least a non-SuperSpeed signal is available. The DisplayPort AUX channel is also supported over the two sideband signals over the same connection; furthermore, [[USB Power Delivery]] according to the newly expanded USB-PD 2.0 specification is possible at the same time. This makes the Type-C connector a strict superset of the use-cases envisioned for DockPort, SlimPort, Mini and Micro DisplayPort.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/8558/displayport-alternate-mode-for-usb-typec-announced | title=DisplayPort Alternate Mode for USB Type-C Announced{{Snd}} Video, Power, & Data All Over Type-D | accessdate = 14 October 2014 | publisher = anandtech.com}}</ref>\n\n=== VirtualLink ===\n{{main|VirtualLink}}\nVirtualLink uses USB-C connectors and DisplayPort to transmit video signals.\n\n== Products ==\n[[File:Lenovo x220 dp crop.jpg|thumb|A [[#Dual-mode|Dual-mode]] DisplayPort connector]]\nSince its introduction in 2006, DisplayPort has gained popularity within the computer industry and is featured on many graphic cards, displays, and notebook computers. Dell was the first company to introduce a consumer product with a DisplayPort connector, the Dell UltraSharp 3008WFP, which was released in January 2008.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/01/03/AR2008010301753_pf.html |title=Dell UltraSharp 3008WFP 30-Inch LCD Monitor |accessdate=25 June 2008 | work=The Washington Post}}</ref> Soon after, [[Advanced Micro Devices|AMD]] and [[Nvidia]] released products to support the technology. AMD included support in the [[Radeon R600|Radeon HD 3000]] series of graphics cards, while Nvidia first introduced support in the [[GeForce 9 series]] starting with the GeForce 9600 GT.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.amd.com/us/press-releases/Pages/Press_Release_124353.aspx | title= AMD Receives First Ever DisplayPort\u2122 Certification for PC Graphics |date= 19 March 2008 |publisher= AMD | accessdate = 23 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"GeForce 9600 GT\">{{cite web |url=http://www.legitreviews.com/article/666/3/ |title=EVGA, Palit and XFX GeForce 9600 GT Video Card Review |last=Kirsch |first=Nathan |date=21 February 2008 |publisher=Legit Reviews |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mini DisplayPort on Apple MacBook.jpg|thumb|left|A Mini DisplayPort connector]]\nLater the same year, Apple introduced several products featuring a Mini DisplayPort.<ref>{{cite web | title = Software Licensing and Trademark Agreement: Mini DisplayPort | url = https://developer.apple.com/softwarelicensing/agreements/minidisplayport.html}}</ref> The new connector{{Snd}} proprietary at the time{{Snd}} eventually became part of the DisplayPort standard, however Apple reserves the right to void the license should the licensee \"commence an action for patent infringement against Apple\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Apple Mini DisplayPort Connector Implementation License Checklist |publisher=Apple |url=https://developer.apple.com/softwarelicensing/agreements/pdf/MiniDisplayPortImpLicense.pdf |accessdate=4 December 2008}}</ref> In 2009, AMD followed suit with their [[Radeon HD 5000 Series]] of graphics cards, which featured the Mini DisplayPort on the ''Eyefinity'' versions in the series.<ref>{{cite web |date=23 September 2009 |url= http://www.pcper.com/article.php?aid=783&type=expert&pid=4 |title=ATI Radeon HD 5870 1GB Graphics Card and AMD Eyefinity Review |publisher=PC Perspective |accessdate=23 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090927152239/http://www.pcper.com/article.php?aid=783&type=expert&pid=4|archive-date=27 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nNvidia launched NVS 810 with 8 Mini DisplayPort outputs on a single card on 4 November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.nvidia.com/blog/2015/11/04/digital-signage-nvs-810/|title=Signs of the Times: Massive Digital Signage Displays Powered by Diminutive Graphics Card|author=|date=|work=The Official NVIDIA Blog|accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\nNvidia revealed the [[GeForce GTX 1080]], the world's first graphics card with DisplayPort 1.4 support on 6 May 2016.<ref>http://www.geforce.com/hardware/10series/geforce-gtx-1080</ref> AMD followed with the Radeon RX 480 to support DisplayPort 1.3/1.4 on 29 June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amd.com/de/products/graphics/radeon-rx-480|title=Radeon\u2122 RX 480-Grafikkarten{{Snd}} AMD|website=www.amd.com}}</ref> The [[List of AMD graphics processing units#Radeon RX 400 Series|Radeon RX 400 Series]] will support DisplayPort 1.3 HBR and HDR10, dropping the DVI connector(s) in the reference board design.\n\nIn February 2017, VESA and Qualcomm announced that DisplayPort Alt Mode video transport will be integrated into the [[Snapdragon]] 835 mobile chipset, which powers smartphones, VR/AR head-mounted displays, IP cameras, tablets and mobile PCs.<ref>[https://www.vesa.org/featured-articles/vesa-highlights-growing-displayport-alt-mode-adoption-and-latest-displayport-developments-at-mobile-world-congress/ VESA Highlights Growing DisplayPort Alt Mode Adoption and Latest DisplayPort Developments at Mobile World Congress]</ref>\n\n=== Support for DisplayPort Alternate Mode over USB-C ===\n{{see also|USB-C#Hardware support}}\n\n== Participating companies{{Anchor|Supporters}}<!--Supporters linked form HDMI--> ==\n'''The following companies have participated in preparing the drafts of DisplayPort, eDP, iDP, DDM or DSC standards''':\n{{Div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* [[Agilent Technologies|Agilent]]\n* [[Altera Corporation|Altera]]\n* [[AMD Graphics Product Group]]\n* [[Analogix]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/analogix-delivers-industrys-first-displayporttm-transmitter-ic-to-also-support-legacy-dvi-to-hdmi-displays-56263647.html |title=Analogix announces DisplayPort transmitter |date=26 August 2006 |accessdate=10 August 2009 |postscript={{inconsistent citations}} |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624223749/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/analogix-delivers-industrys-first-displayporttm-transmitter-ic-to-also-support-legacy-dvi-to-hdmi-displays-56263647.html |archivedate=24 June 2013 |df=dmy }}.</ref>\n* [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]\n* [[Astrodesign]]\n* [[BenQ]]\n* [[Broadcom|Broadcom Corporation]]\n* [[Chi Mei Optoelectronics]]\n* [[Chrontel]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.chrontel.com/ | title = Chrontel }}</ref>\n* [[Dell]]\n* [[Display Labs]]\n* [[Foxconn|Foxconn Electronics]]\n* [[FuturePlus Systems]]\n* [[Genesis Microchip]]<ref>{{cite web |date=2 May 2006 |url= http://seekingalpha.com/article/9956 |title= Genesis Microchip (GNSS) Q4 2006 Earnings Conference Call | publisher=Seeking Alpha |accessdate=16 July 2007}}</ref>\n* [[Gigabyte Technology]]\n* [[Hardent]]\n* [[Hewlett-Packard]]\n* [[Hosiden]]\n* [[Hirose Electric Group]]\n* [[Intel Corporation|Intel]]\n* [[intoPIX]]\n* [[I-PEX]]\n* [[Integrated Device Technology]]\n* [[Japan Aviation Electronics|JAE Electronics]]\n* [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries|Kawasaki Microelectronics (K-Micro)]]\n* [[Keysight Technologies]]\n* [[Lenovo]]\n* [[LG Display]]\n* [[Luxtera]]\n* [[Molex]]\n* [[NEC]]\n* [[NVIDIA]]\n* [[NXP Semiconductors]]\n* [[Xi3 Corporation]]\n* [[Parade Technologies]]\n* [[Realtek|Realtek Semiconductor]]\n* [[Samsung Electronics|Samsung]]<ref>{{cite web |date=25 July 2006 |url=http://www.tgdaily.com/content/view/33064/135/ |title=Samsung touts development of first DisplayPort desktop LCD |publisher=TG Daily |accessdate=25 July 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926232615/http://www.tgdaily.com/content/view/33064/135/ |archivedate=26 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* SMK\n* [[STMicroelectronics]]\n* [[SyntheSys Research Inc.]]\n* [[Tektronix]]\n* [[Texas Instruments]]\n* [[Technology Leaders & Innovators|TLi]]\n* [[Tyco Electronics]]\n* [[ViewSonic]]\n* VTM\n{{div col end}}\n\n'''The following companies have additionally announced their intention to implement DisplayPort, eDP or iDP''':\n{{Div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* [[Acer Inc.|Acer]]\n* [[ASRock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asrock.com/news/show.asp?id=119|title=Worldwide First DisplayPort MB|date=25 March 2008|accessdate=10 August 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090115205813/http://www.asrock.com/news/show.asp?id=119|archivedate=15 January 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Biostar]]\n* Chroma\n* [[BlackBerry Ltd.|BlackBerry]]\n* [[Circuit Assembly]]\n* DataPro<ref>{{ cite web | url=http://www.datapro.net/catalog/displayport-cables.html | title=DataPro DisplayPort Cables }}</ref>\n* [[Eizo]]\n* [[Fujitsu]]\n* [[Hall Research Technologies]]\n* [[ITE Tech. Inc.|ITE Tech.]]\n* [[Matrox Graphics]]\n* [[Micro-Star International]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ca.msi.com/index.php?func=newsdesc&news_no=578 |title=MSI announces video adaptor with DisplayPort |date=17 January 2008 |accessdate=10 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219021343/http://ca.msi.com/index.php?func=newsdesc&news_no=578 |archivedate=19 December 2013 }}</ref>\n* MStar Semiconductor\n* Novatek Microelectronics Corp.\n* [[Palit Microsystems Ltd.]]\n* [[Pioneer Corporation]]\n* [[S3 Graphics]]\n* [[Toshiba]]\n* [[Philips]]\n* [[Quantum Data]]\n* [[Sparkle Computer]]\n* [[Unigraf]]\n* [[Xitrix]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[HDBaseT]]\n* [[HDMI]]\n* [[List of video connectors]]\n* [[Thunderbolt (interface)]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=60em|group=\"note\"}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Note please read [[WP:EL]] before putting links here. -->\n* [http://socialcompare.com/fr/comparison/connecteurs-informatiques-interfaces-ecrans-et-audio-3yzkq9hm# Crowdsourced comparison table EN-FR video connectors]\n* {{official website|name=DisplayPort}}{{Snd}} the official site operated by VESA\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120403034135/http://www.edn.com/article/472107-Bridging_the_new_DisplayPort_standard.php Bridging the new DisplayPort standard] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111010172142/http://www.hardwaresecrets.com/article/Introducing-the-Panel-Self-Refresh-Technology/1384 Introducing the Panel Self Refresh Technology]\n* [http://www.slimportconnect.com/ SlimPort Consumer website]\n* [http://www.slimportconnect.com/slimport-supported-devices SlimPort Enabled Devices]\n\n{{AVconn}}\n{{Audio and video interfaces and connectors}}\n{{Basic computer components}}\n{{Digital audio and video protocols}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Displayport}}\n[[Category:Digital display connectors]]\n[[Category:VESA]]\n[[Category:Computer connectors]]\n", "name_user": "OlliverWithDoubleL", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DisplayPort"}
{"title_page": "Trixie Mattel", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Trixie Mattel\n| image              = Rupaul Dragcon 2018-103 (41175949055) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Mattel at [[RuPaul's DragCon LA]] 2018\n| birth_name         = Brian Michael Firkus\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|mf=yas|1989|8|23}}\n| birth_place        = [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]], U.S. \n| residence          = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Milwaukee]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Professional drag queen|singer-songwriter|comedian|television personality}}\n| yearsactive        = 2008\u2013present\n| known_for          = {{hlist|''[[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 7)|RuPaul's Drag Race]]''|''[[RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars (season 3)|RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars]]''|''[[UNHhhh]]''|''[[The Trixie & Katya Show]]''}}\n| predecessor        = [[Alaska Thunderfuck 5000|Alaska]]\n| successor          = [[Trinity Taylor]] and [[Mon\u00e9t X Change]]\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yas\n| background = solo_singer\n| instrument = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|clarinet|autoharp}}\n| genre = [[Country folk]], [[Americana (music)|Americana]]\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Katya Zamolodchikova]]|[[Bob the Drag Queen]]|[[Pearl (drag queen)|Pearl]]|[[Kim Chi (drag queen)|Kim Chi]]|[[RuPaul]]}}\n| label =\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Trixie Mattel''' is the drag persona of '''Brian Michael Firkus''' (born August 23, 1989),<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/trixie-mattel-mn0003634361/biography|title=Trixie Martel : Biography|last1=Monger|first1=James Christopher|date=August 2017|publisher=[[AllMusic.com]] ([[All Media Network]])|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref> an American [[drag queen]], singer-songwriter, comedian, and [[television personality]] from [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]]. Mattel is known for being the winner of the [[RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars (season 3)|third season]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars]]'', and for placing sixth on the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 7)|seventh season]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]''.\n\nMattel co-hosts the [[web series]] ''[[UNHhhh]]'' and its [[Viceland]] follow-up ''[[The Trixie & Katya Show]]'' alongside [[Katya Zamolodchikova]]. Her first studio album, ''[[Two Birds (album)|Two Birds]]'', was released in 2017, followed by her second album, ''[[One Stone]]'', in 2018. Her third album, ''[[Barbara (Trixie Mattel album)|Barbara]]'' was released February 7, 2020.\n\nMattel is also the CEO of Trixie Cosmetics, her cosmetics brand.\n\n==Early life==\nFirkus was born in [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> He is half [[Ojibwe]] and comes from a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] family living in [[Crivitz, Wisconsin]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brooke|first1=Zach|title=Point of View: Trixie Mattel|url= https://www.milwaukeemag.com/2015/09/08/qa-trixie-mattel/|website=[[Milwaukee Magazine]]|publisher=[[Quad/Graphics]]|date=September 8, 2015|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://webelieveproject.wordpress.com/2015/05/13/when-you-are-true-to-yourself-amazing-things-can-happen/ When you are true to yourself amazing things can happen | This We Believe] Retrieved September 10, 2018.</ref> He had an abusive stepfather who would call him a \"trixie\" when he acted feminine, which would later inspire his drag name. He almost went by the name Cupcake before deciding on Trixie.<ref>{{mattel|title=Living Doll: Trixie Mattel|work=[[Metro Weekly]]|publisher=|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> After graduating high school, Firkus attended the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Milwaukee]], where he received a BFA in Music Theatre<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wisconsingazette.com/entertainment/for-brian-firkus-a-childhood-slur-became-the-springboard-for/article_73f168f7-1e1c-567a-8386-e1acc6fcdb2e.html |title=For Brian Firkus, a childhood slur became the springboard for success as Trixie Mattel  |last1=Kennedy |first1=Kerrie |date=June 3, 2015 |website=Wisconsin Gazette |publisher= |accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref> and was introduced to drag while performing in a production of ''[[The Rocky Horror Show]]'' at the [[Oriental Theatre (Milwaukee)|Oriental Theatre]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyxtra.com/a-filthy-starry-night-with-trixie-mattel-67999|title=A filthy, starry night with Trixie Mattel|last1=Yerxa |first1=Mike |date=June 25, 2015|website=[[Daily Xtra]]|publisher=[[Pink Triangle Press]]|access-date=August 12, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHe first performed in drag in 2008, at LaCage NiteClub in Milwaukee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://host.madison.com/ct/news/local/city-life/plan-b-host-trixie-mattel-to-strut-her-stuff-on/article_8cf12a91-fe1b-5ddf-bcf3-f30d750ae206.html |title=Plan B host Trixie Mattel to strut her stuff on 'RuPaul's Drag Race' |last1=Christians |first1=Lindasy |date=December 10, 2014 |website=[[The Capital Times]] |publisher= |accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref> Firkus became a staple of the Milwaukee drag scene while also performing in [[Chicago]] alongside other acts introduced on ''RuPaul's Drag Race'', such as [[Kim Chi (drag queen)|Kim Chi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.jsonline.com/entertainment/arts/milwaukee-drag-queen-trixie-mattel-wins-spot-on-rupauls-drag-race-b99404841z1-285037501.html |title=Milwaukee drag queen Trixie Mattel wins spot on \"RuPaul's Drag Race\" |last1=Schumacher |first1=Mary Louise |date=December 7, 2014 |website=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] |publisher=[[Gannett Company]] |accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/rupauls-drag-race-queens-best-friends/|title=RuPaul's Drag Race: 7 Queens Who Are Best Friends (And 8 Who Are Frenemies)|date=April 15, 2018|website=ScreenRant|language=en-US|access-date=January 16, 2019}}</ref> In 2014, Firkus attended [[Aveda|The Institute of Beauty and Wellness]] before withdrawing later that same year to participate in ''RuPaul's Drag Race''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.timeout.com/chicago/blog/trixie-mattel-from-rupauls-drag-race-to-perform-in-chicago |title=Trixie Mattel from RuPaul's Drag Race to perform in Chicago |last1=Guerino |first1=Adam |date=June 9, 2015 |website=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] |publisher= |accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n===''RuPaul's Drag Race''===\nAs a competitor in [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 7)|Season 7]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'', Mattel was eliminated in episode four and later reentered the competition in episode eight by winning the \"Conjoined Twins\" challenge with [[Pearl (drag queen)|Pearl Liaison]]. Mattel was once again eliminated in episode 10,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/matthew-terrell/trixie-mattel-elimination_b_6936636.html|title=Trixie Mattel Elimination Casts Doubt on RPDR Reality|last1=Terrell|first1=Matthew|date=March 26, 2015|website=[[HuffPost|The Huffington Post]]|publisher=AOL Inc|access-date=December 4, 2016}}</ref> placing sixth overall and becoming the first queen to last more than one episode after returning to the competition.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nMattel later returned for the [[RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars (season 3)|third season]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race: All Stars]]'', which started airing on January 25, 2018. On March 15, 2018, her fellow competitors voted for her to advance to the final two, where she ultimately won against runner-up [[Kennedy Davenport]] in the final lipsync battle.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tvline.com/2018/03/15/rupauls-drag-race-all-stars-trixie-mattel-wins-season-3-finale-recap/|title=RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars Finale: Did the Right Queen Win Season 3?|last=Swift|first=Andy|date=March 16, 2018|work=TVLine|access-date=March 16, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/921102/rupaul-s-drag-race-all-stars-3-crowns-a-winner|title=RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars 3 Crowns a Winner|work=E! Online|access-date=March 16, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nShe competed in the 2018 television special ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race Holi-slay Spectacular]]'' and won alongside the other competitors.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8482663/rupauls-drag-race-holiday-spectacular-trixie-shangela|title=Kim Chi, Shangela, Trixie Mattel & More to Compete in 'RuPaul's Drag Race Holi-Slay Spectacular'|work=Billboard|access-date=November 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZSbFfSm0DgM|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com|access-date=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other ventures===\n[[File:Trixie and Katya's High School Reunion 3.jpg|thumb|right|[[Katya Zamolodchikova]] with Trixie Mattel]]\nAfter competing on ''Drag Race'', on December 31, 2015, Mattel guest starred in a special edition of [[World of Wonder (production company)|WOWPresents]]' Fashion Photo Review<ref>{{Citation|last=WOWPresents|title=Trixie & Katya's Fashion Photo RuView, RuView of Raja & Raven|date=December 31, 2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xUtKgqq4epM&index=1&list=PLVmMNOHpsWfkF7E-ZYg_mufJfF6_xJBim|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref> with fellow season seven contestant [[Katya Zamolodchikova]], which later launched ''[[UNHhhh]]'', that premiered on March 25, 2016. The duo later went on to star in ''[[The Trixie & Katya Show]]'', which premiered on [[Viceland]] on November 15, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.papermag.com/hold-on-to-your-wigs-katya-and-trixie-mattel-are-getting-their-own-tv-show-2474558266.html|title=Hold On to Your Wigs: Katya and Trixie Mattel Are Getting Their Own TV Show|last1=Cuby|first1=Michael|date=August 18, 2017|work=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trixie-and-katya-show-tvs-best-new-talk-show-hosts-are-two-drag-queens|title='Trixie and Katya Show': TV's Best New Talk Show Hosts Are Two Drag Queens|first=Kevin|last=Fallon|date=November 15, 2017|publisher=|via=www.thedailybeast.com}}</ref> Also in November 2017, Trixie and Katya starred in a drag stage adaptation of the 1997 cult film ''[[Romy and Michele's High School Reunion]]'', entitled ''Trixie and Katya's High School Reunion''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/trixie-mattel-katya-romy-michele-high-school-reunion/11/2017/|title=Trixie Mattel And Katya Recreated The \"Romy And Michele\" Dance Sequence\u2014And It Was Perfection|website=newnownext.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldofwonder.net/absolutely-hysterical-trixie-katya-recreate-romy-michele-dance-sequence/|title=Absolutely Hysterical: Trixie & Katya Recreate that Iconic \"Romy And Michele\" Dance Sequence|date=November 21, 2017|website=worldofwonder.net}}</ref>\n\nMattel has toured around the world with her stand-up comedy show called \"Ages 3 and Up\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.trixiemattel.com/event/trixie-mattel-ages-3-and-up/|title=\"Trixie Mattel: Ages 3 and Up\" {{!}} Trixie Mattel|work=Trixie Mattel|access-date=October 16, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> In October 2017, Mattel streamed on the live video gaming platform [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] alongside 8BitDylan to raise money for the [[GaymerX]] foundation and many other charities before and since.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/EightBitDylan/status/916009357954789376|title=This Sunday catch @trixiemattel and myself play some games to raise money for the @GaymerX foundation! 6PM CST|last=(8Bit)|first=Dylan|date=October 5, 2017|website=@EightBitDylan|language=en|access-date=December 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nTrixie has toured on the \"Haters Roast: The Shady Tour\" with other queens from ''RuPaul's Drag Race'', such as [[Jinkx Monsoon]] and [[Thorgy Thor]] for their 2017 and 2018 alumni tours.\n\nIn February 2018, she announced her new comedy tour \"Now with Moving Parts\", which began in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/trixiemattel/status/966038334576386048|title=First 9 cities announced! DragFans.com|date=February 20, 2018|website=@trixiemattel|language=en|access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA documentary film titled ''[[Trixie Mattel: Moving Parts]]'' premiered at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] in April 2019, and screened until May 2019. It documents Mattel as she embarks on her \"Moving Parts\" tour following her ''All Stars'' win, as well as her personal struggles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8501229/trixie-mattel-documentary-2019-tribeca-film-festival-premiere|title=Trixie Mattel Documentary Set to Premiere at 2019 Tribeca Film Festival|date=March 5, 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> The documentary will be available on [[Video On Demand]] platforms on December 3, 2019. An accompanying acoustic soundtrack is set for release later in December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/11/15/trixie-mattel-moving-parts-release-date/|title=Trixie Mattel's Moving Parts documentary finally has a release date|last=Nolfi|first=Joey|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|date=November 15, 2019|accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 1, 2019, Mattel announced that she will be releasing her make-up brand \"Trixie Cosmetics\" later that month, with the products launching at RuPaul's DragCon LA on May 24, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.out.com/celebs/2019/5/01/trixie-mattel-launching-her-own-beauty-brand|title=Trixie Mattel Is Launching Her Own Beauty Brand|magazine=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]|last=Dommu|first=Rose|publisher=Joe Landry|date=May 1, 2019|accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Mattel was one of 37 queens to be featured on the cover of [[New York Magazine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nymag.com/press/2019/06/on-the-cover-the-most-powerful-drag-queens-in-america.html|title=On New York's 37 Covers: The Most Powerful Drag Queens in America|date=June 10, 2019|website=New York Press Room}}</ref>\n\nMattel's first comedy special, ''Trixie Mattel: Skinny Legend'', aired on [[OutTV]] in Canada on September 26, 2019.<ref name=\"Rudolph\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/drag-race-comedy-specials-out-tv-trixie-mattel/07/2019/|title=\"Drag Race\" Alums Return to TV in New Documentary, Comedy Specials|last=Rudolph|first=Christopher|publisher=NewNowNext|date=July 24, 2019|accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nMattel released the [[country folk]] album ''[[Two Birds (album)|Two Birds]]'' in May 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/two-birds/id1225829683|title=Two Birds by Trixie Mattel on iTunes|publisher=iTunes|language=en|access-date=April 30, 2017}}</ref> Her second album, ''[[One Stone]]'', was released on March 15, 2018, the same night as the ''RuPaul's Drag Race: All Stars'' finale.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/trixie-mattel-interview-one-stone-drag-race-all-stars_uk_5aaa58bce4b0f4aaa1141bbe|title=Trixie Mattel Reflects On Her 'All Stars' Performance And New Album 'One Stone'|date=March 15, 2018|work=HuffPost UK|access-date=March 16, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Mattel listed her primary influences as [[June Carter Cash]] and [[Dolly Parton]] and states that she grew up on the music of [[George Jones]], [[Conway Twitty]] and [[Johnny Cash]]. She is also a fan of [[Jason Isbell]], [[Kris Kristofferson]], [[Aimee Mann]] and [[Kacey Musgraves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/features/rupaul-drag-race-trixie-mattel-country-albums-kacey-musgraves-w518524|title=Drag Queen Trixie Mattel on Her Country Albums, Kacey Musgraves Obsession|website=rollingstone.com|date=March 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a September 2018 interview with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', she announced that she is working on her third studio album that will feature an \"[[electro-folk]]\" sound and is going to be called ''[[Barbara (Trixie Mattel album)|Barbara]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8474050/trixie-mattel-electro-folk-album-eminem|title=Trixie Mattel Talks Upcoming 'Electro-Folk' Album & Shares Erotic Eminem Fantasy|website=Billboard}}</ref> \"Yellow Cloud\" was released as the first single from the album on May 17, 2019, though it was later revealed to be a non-album single. On January 10, 2020, the album's release date was confirmed for February 7, 2020, alongside the album tracklist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8547761/trixie-mattel-barbara-album-teaser-video|title=Trixie Mattel Is Bringing Fans to the Beach With Official 'Barbara' Album Teaser: Watch|website=Billboard|last=Daw|first=Stephen|date=January 10, 2020|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nFirkus is openly [[gay]].<ref>{{cite tweet|number=888511437009698817|user=trixiemattel|title=I'm a gay person who specializes in gay activities.|date=July 21, 2017}}</ref> He has been in a relationship with filmmaker David Silver, who is the producer of his documentary, ''Moving Parts'', for three years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.queerty.com/trixie-mattel-time-moms-boyfriend-pulled-gun-teen-queen-20190428|title= Trixie Mattel on Katya\u2019s mental breakdown caught on film in her dragumentary, \u2018Moving Parts\u2019|website=Queerty|last=Reddish|first=David|date=April 28, 2019|accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref> He is also a [[vegetarian]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=trixiemattel|number=610533359714893824|title=I'm a vegetarian !|date=June 15, 2015|accessdate=September 19, 2018|url-status=live|archivedate=May 19, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180519175211/https://twitter.com/trixiemattel/status/610533359714893824}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|accessdate=September 19, 2018|user=trixiemattel|number=1012961007453528067|title=Triggered. Also I\u2019m a vegetarian.|date=June 30, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920022742/https://twitter.com/trixiemattel/status/1012961007453528067|archivedate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Tracy Martel has an obsession over [[Barbie|Barbie Dolls]], owning a wide collection of Barbies in her Los Angeles home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/trixie-mattel-on-the-nostalgic-dolls-that-inspired-her-1840489833|title=Trixie Mattel on the Barbies that inspired her upcoming world tour|first=Marah|last=Eakin|date=December 19, 2019|website=AV Club|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n! {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2015\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]''\n| Herself (contestant)\n| [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 7)|Season 7]], 6th place\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/mar/03/rupauls-drag-race-recap-season-seven-episode-one-the-devil-wears-nada|title=RuPaul's Drag Race recap: season seven, episode one \u2013 the devil wears nada|last1=Carpentier |first1=Megan |last2=Rushe |first2=Dominic|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=March 3, 2015|accessdate=June 7, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n| Herself (guest)\n| [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 8)|Season 8]], Episode 10: \"Grand Finale\"\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[RuPaul's Drag Race: Untucked]]''\n|Herself\n|Season 7\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[American Horror Story: Roanoke]]''\n|Herself\n|Season 6, Episode 10: \"[[Chapter 10 (American Horror Story)|Chapter 10]]\"\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newnownext.com/american-horror-story-trixie-mattel/11/2016/ |title=Trixie Mattel Pops Up In The \"American Horror Story\" Season Finale |last1=Avery |first1=Dan |date=November 17, 2016 |website=[[Logo TV#Online|NewNowNext]] |publisher=[[Viacom Media Networks]] |accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Gay for Play Game Show Starring RuPaul]]''\n|Herself\n|Season 1, Episode 5: \"Featuring Mindy Cohn\"<br>